What is an Accessible Name?

01
On this page
  1. Ways to Add Accessible Names
    1. aria-label
    2. aria-labelledby
    3. title
  2. The Accessible Name and Description Computation Spec

Accessible names are a way of labeling elements that inform people using Assistive Technology of the purpose of that element.

Many kinds of elements work with accessible names. Buttons, links, inputs, selects, landmarks… the list goes on.

We’ve already seen some examples of accessible naming in this workshop when using ARIA labels.

In the date picker, we added an aria-label to provide additional context to a button that would otherwise only announce a number.

Ways to Add Accessible Names

aria-label

As we’ve, seen aria-label all allows us to specify a string to use as a name if we don’t want to go with the default of whatever text is inside the element. Note that it is still necessary to include the text shown on screen in the aria-label so it can be identified with voice navigation tools.

aria-labelledby

We can do a similar thing with the aria-labelledby property, but instead of supplying our own name we set the label to the inner text of some other element by pointing at its id. We’ll see an example of this in a bit.

title

Adding a title creates a description that will be optionally read aloud after an accessible name (meaning it can create redundancy). It can also contribute to an accessible name as a fallback and is commonly used to label iframes. But it will only show up visually for mouse users. If you use title, be sure to test it.

The Accessible Name and Description Computation Spec

You may recall learning about aria-label taking preference over text content in an element for its accessible name. What happens if you have aria-label, aria-labelledby, title, and text content on the same element? (Which one should win out in a screen reader announcement?)

Browsers didn’t pull these attributes out of nowhere and decide they should work a certain way.

They are all part of the W3C’s Accessible Name and Description Computation specification, which outlines processes related to adding names and descriptions to elements and how this information is used by Assistive Technology.

Inside of the terminology section of the spec is the algorithm for how the actual “text alternative” (accessible name) is computed.

It ends up there’s quite a lot of decision making involved!

Throughout this section and the rest of the workshop we will practice with adding accessible names to our components and elements.
